<p>
  From zero to first customer, then from first customer to multiple teams and
  thousands of users: I've walked that path twice, on Progicar (B2B SaaS) and
  Passion Barbecue (e-commerce).
</p>
<p>
  Early on, that means picking a stack you can live with, shipping an MVP fast
  without painting yourself into a corner, and knowing which technical debt you
  take on deliberately rather than by accident. As the product grows, it means
  structuring teams, industrialising what used to be patched together, and
  handing off the topics a single founder can no longer carry.
</p>
<p>Concretely useful for:</p>
<ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
  <li>
    <strong>early-stage startups</strong> looking for a founding or fractional CTO
    to frame their first technical choices;
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>non-technical founders</strong> who want to avoid the classic first-MVP
    pitfalls;
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>teams that shipped an MVP</strong> and aren't sure how to scale up without
    a full rewrite.
  </li>
</ul>
